{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2724"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2724"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.47,0.12,0.07,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78812"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64161"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"1258"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43865"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78812"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 67-year-old woman presents with a 12 month history of early satiety, post-prandial epigastric discomfort and heartburn. She does not take any medications, is a non-smoker and drinks four glasses of wine a week. The physical examination is unremarkable and she is referred for a specialist opinion. Investigations, including an endoscopy, at that time showed a para-oesophageal hernia and no other abnormalities in her upper digestive tract. Her haemoglobin is 130 g/L (115-165). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is referred for a surgical opinion for consideration of repair of her hernia. When reviewed two months later her symptoms have remained unchanged and she is keen to go through with surgery. Her haemoglobin is 107 g/L (iron deficient).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Apart from considering a repeat endoscopy, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Red cell scan","Colonoscopy","CT chest and abdomen","Proceed with hernia repair","Iron infusion and proceed with hernia repair"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had a substantial drop in her haemoglobin in a relatively short period of time. She has an iron deficiency anaemia and this is most likely due to occult bleeding from within her digestive tract. Since she did not have any other obvious explanation for this her, thought must be given to excluding other potential sources of bleeding. Whilst she could have a Cameron\u0027s ulcer, no such abnormality was seen on the initial endoscopy and a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed to exclude a colonic malignancy. If this is normal, a repeat endoscopy could be considered. If the patient felt strongly that she would not have a colonoscopy, a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT of the chest and abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered. Any consideration of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehernia repair\u003C/strong\u003E should be deferred until a clear reason for the anaemia is found. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ered cell scan \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be performed if the endoscopy and colonoscopy were both normal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastrointestinal tract malignancy must always be considered as a cause of iron deficiency anaemia in an otherwise healthy older patient.","Colonoscopy is an essential investigation in the work-up of iron deficiency anaemia to exclude lower gastrointestinal bleeding sources."],"references":["Camaschella C. Iron-deficiency anemia. N Engl J Med. 2015 May 7;372(19):1832-43. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1401038. PMID: 25946282. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25946282/","Camaschella C. Iron deficiency. Blood. 2019 Jan 3;133(1):30-39. doi: 10.1182/blood-2018-05-815944. Epub 2018 Nov 6. Erratum in: Blood. 2023 Feb 09;141(6):682. doi: 10.1182/blood.2022018610. PMID: 30401704. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30401704/","Stephens MR, Hopper AN, White SR, Jugool S, Stratford R, Lewis WG, Allison MC. Colonoscopy first for iron-deficiency anaemia: a Numbers Needed to Investigate approach. QJM. 2006 Jun;99(6):389-95. doi: 10.1093/qjmed/hcl053. Epub 2006 May 8. PMID: 16682438. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16682438/","Banerjee AK, Celentano V, Khan J, Longcroft-Wheaton G, Quine A, Bhandari P. Practical gastrointestinal investigation of iron deficiency anaemia. Expert Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2018 Mar;12(3):249-256. doi: 10.1080/17474124.2018.1404905. Epub 2017 Nov 20. Erratum in: Expert Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2018 Mar;12(3):i. doi: 10.1080/17474124.2018.1415794. PMID: 29129158. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29129158/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2724"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","